<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>be whole of mind • be whole-minded</xh5><p> <i>be whole of mind</i>—(arch., formal) be mentally normal; be of sound mind <i>(used in wills and trusts</i>): I Richard Ballard of Orbye being <u>whole of mind</u> and perfect of remembrance make my last will and testament.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> a) The expression is not equivalent in meaning to the phrase <b>whole of mind and body</b>—safe and sound; unharmed: We just hoped that he would come home from his tour <u>whole of mind and body</u>.</p><p> b) The expression is not antonymous in meaning to the phrase <b>have half a mind</b>—feel tempted or inclined to do something: I <u>had half a mind</u> to drown myself then; but an odd wish to see the whole adventure out ... restrained me.</p><p><i>be whole-minded—</i>be completely dedicated to smth.: Even if Bu Kiwon was crazy (which, of course, he was not), he obviously <u>was whole-minded</u> enough to create trouble for the League!</p> </entry>
